Tried many of the top-ranked "Free" Mag apps, and all (really) of the paid ones that had a free version, and THIS is the BEST one. Many of the others are copies of themselves under 3 different names; same for the paid apps, a few are the same under different names. And almost all have the same bug: They increase screen brightness to MAX and do NOT return it to what it was when you exit the app. Cozy Mag has no such issue, you can pick the brightness, and it returns correctly to what it was when you exit. And the Mag Level slider is custom - not the standard Material Design slider with the tiny tiny blue dot that you cannot for the life of you "grab" and move; no such problem with Cozy Mag. Has all the features of the best Mag apps, like Freeze and Color Adjustments. Even has an unusual one: Exposure (suggest you leave that alone, or you will not be able to put it back to 50% exactly.) Oh, and it saves the pictures in a folder inside DCIM, unlike some others that dump their pictures outside of the image gallery. 5/5.

I am legally blind and have always carried around a pocket magnifier to view up close things (pretty much any font smaller than 14 pt) and a pocket monocular for things at a distance (e.g. fast food restaurant menu).  This app has all but replaced both of these assistive devices.  I do still carry them around with me - after all these years, I feel naked without them - but only ever resort to them if the  battery is dead in my phone.    This says a lot about how well this app works.  Like many others, I tried many other apps before and this one is, by far, the best of the bunch.  My only complaint (and I won't dock any points for this) is that the icon could be a little better...it's just not as pretty as many other apps.  Oh, and, although the app doesn't need it, i feel that it should have an options menu.  It just feels like something is missing when an app doesn't have an options menu.  Oh, actually, I do have one legitimate complaint/suggestion.  The buttons/icons in the app aren't always self explanatory.  Perhaps add the option to display a label for each control when you touch and hold it.  That's how the current Gmail app works.

I tried the free version first, and after finding out this app does what I need I immediately purchased the full version for a mear 99 cents. We all need to support the developers when they create useful, good apps.  This app does what I need: help in reading very small print. Cozy Magnifier is very easy to use, starts up quick, and allows for real-time pinch-n-zoom. It also has a button to turn on the camera's light, which is great for dark environments. For someone over 40 who needs help reading small print, this app is a life saver! I highly recommend it. I've got it running on my HTC EVO LTE smartphone with the latest version of the Jelly Bean OS.
